doc.ContractDescription: THE PURPOSE OF THIS WORK IS A 2-YEAR CAMPAIGN TO STUDY SEVEN RADIO GALAXIES WITH THE AIM OF INVESTIGATING THE ORIGIN, STRUCTURE AND NATURE OF NON-BLAZAR ACTIVE GALACTIC NUCLEI (AGN). RADIO GALAXIES ARE AGN WITH THE RELATIVISTIC JET NON ALIGNED WITH THE OBSERVER'S LINE OF SIGHT. THEY ARE MORE CHALLENGING TO DETECT IN GAMMA RAYS, BUT THE MISALIGNED JET ALLOWS TO INVESTIGATE THE SUB-STRUCTURES OF THE REGION RESPONSIBLE FOR GAMMA-RAY EMISSION. THE DATA THAT FORM THE BASIS OF THE WORK ARE ANTICIPATED VERITAS DATA, PROCESSED FERMI-LAT DATA, AND X-RAY TIMING AND IMAGING DATA. THE PI IS ALREADY AN EXPERT IN THE ANALYSIS OF ALL THESE PRODUCTS, WILL COORDINATE THE DATA TAKING AND WILL PERFORM REGULAR ANALYSIS AND MONITORING OF THE DATA. THE FERMI-GI PROGRAM'S PANEL FOUND THE SCIENTIFIC ARGUMENTS COMPELLING AND BELIEVED THAT IT IS VERY IMPORTANT TO INVESTIGATE THE EMISSION PROPERTIES OF THESE NON BLAZAR SOURCES. THE PROPOSAL RESEARCH IS DIRECTLY RELATED TO THE MAJOR NASA RESEARCH OBJECTIVE AND STRATEGIC SUB-GOAL 3D: DISCOVER THE ORIGIN, STRUCTURE, EVOLUTION AND DESTINY OF THE UNIVERSE, AND SEARCH FOR EARTH-LIKE PLANETS.

SURFACE OPERATIONS PLAY A MAJOR PART IN THE EFFICIENCY OF THE AIR TRANSPORTATION SYSTEM, BUT ALSO CONTRIBUTE TO THE FUEL BURN, EMISSIONS, AIR QUALITY AND NOISE IMPACTS OF AIRCRAFT OPERATIONS AT AIRPORTS. OZONE (O3) AND PARTICULATE MATTER (PM) ARE OF PARTICULAR IMPORTANCE TO AIR QUALITY, MORE SO AS MANY MAJOR US AIRPORTS LIE IN NON-ATTAINMENT AREAS. THE ACCURATE ASSESSMENT OF THESE ENVIRONMENTAL IMPACTS IS THEREFORE IMPORTANT BOTH FOR THE DESIGN OF NEXTGEN CONCEPTS SUCH AS SURFACE TRAJECTORY-BASED OPERATIONS, AND THE DEVELOPMENT OF NEAR-TERM OPERATIONAL PROCEDURE ENHANCEMENTS. MIT, MOSAIC ATM, AND ATAC PROPOSE A COMPREHENSIVE RESEARCH PLAN FOR THE ASSESSMENT OF O3 AND PM-RELATED IMPACTS DUE TO AIRPORT SURFACE OPERATIONS. THE APPROACH WILL INCLUDE THE DEVELOPMENT AND VALIDATION OF REAL-TIME MODELS THAT EVALUATE EMISSIONS IMPACTS (AND THE ASSOCIATED AIR QUALITY IMPACTS) OF AIRCRAFT SURFACE TRAJECTORIES. THESE MODELS WILL BE INTEGRATED WITH NASA'S SURFACE MANAGEMENT SYSTEM (SMS), AND A PLAN WILL BE DEVELOPED FOR THE INTEGRATION OF THE PROPOSED MODELS WITH FAA'S AVIATION ENVIRONMENTAL DESIGN TOOL (AEDT). THE PROPOSED APPROACH WILL INCLUDE: 1) A SURVEY OF EXISTING STATE-OF-THE-ART MODELS. THERE HAS BEEN PRIOR RESEARCH ON ESTIMATING O3 AND PM IMPACTS OF AIRPORT OPERATIONS, INCLUDING BY RESEARCHERS INVOLVED IN THE CURRENT EFFORT. IN PARTICULAR, MIT HAS EXTENSIVE EXPERIENCE IN ESTIMATING EMISSIONS AND DEVELOPING RAPID AIR QUALITY MODELS SUITABLE FOR ASSESSING AIR QUALITY IMPACTS IN NEAR REAL TIME. WE WILL CONDUCT A SURVEY OF THESE MODELS, THEIR LIMITATIONS, UNDERLYING UNCERTAINTIES, AND GAPS IN CURRENT KNOWLEDGE. 2) TRANSLATION OF SURFACE AIRCRAFT TRAJECTORIES INTO AIR QUALITY IMPACTS. THIS TASK WILL INVOLVE THE DEVELOPMENT/REFINEMENT OF MODELS AS NEEDED. THE KEY CHALLENGE IS THAT THE AIR QUALITY IMPACTS DEPEND ON FACTORS SUCH AS AMBIENT ATMOSPHERIC CONDITIONS, POLLUTANTS (SUCH AS CO, NOX, HC, BC, OC, SOX) EMITTED BY THE AIRCRAFT ENGINES, ETC. THE EMISSION RATES THEMSELVES DEPEND ON FACTORS INCLUDING THE ENGINE TYPE, THRUST SETTING AND FUEL FLOW RATE. THE FUEL FLOW RATES IN TURN DEPEND ON AIRCRAFT TYPES AND ENGINE THRUST SETTING, WHICH POTENTIALLY CHANGE DEPENDING ON THE SURFACE TRAJECTORIES AS THE PILOT ACCELERATES, SLOWS DOWN, ETC. WE THEREFORE PROPOSE TO USE OPERATIONAL FLIGHT DATA RECORDER INFORMATION TO BUILD MODELS THAT DETERMINE THE FUEL FLOW RATE VARIATION WITH TIME GIVEN A SURFACE TRAJECTORY, WHICH WILL BE MAPPED TO PROBABILISTIC ESTIMATES OF EMISSIONS. THESE EMISSIONS WILL BE USED IN RAPID AIR QUALITY MODELS. 3) PROOF-OF-CONCEPT VALIDATION. THE PROPOSED APPROACH WILL BE DEMONSTRATED USING SIMULATIONS OF SURFACE OPERATIONS AT 3 US AIRPORTS OVER 2 DAYS. THE SCENARIOS (AIRPORTS AND DATES) WILL BE CHOSEN IN CONSULTATION WITH NASA RESEARCHERS, AND WILL CONSIDER FACTORS SUCH AS ATMOSPHERIC CONDITIONS, AIRPORT LAYOUTS, NON-ATTAINMENT AREAS AND AIRCRAFT FLEET MIX. 4) PLANS FOR INTEGRATION WITH SMS AND AEDT. THE MODELS WILL BE DEVELOPED IN A MANNER THAT IS AMENABLE TO INTEGRATION WITH SMS AND AEDT. DETAILED PLANS FOR SOFTWARE INTEGRATION WILL BE DEVELOPED. MIT CONTRIBUTED TO CURRENT AEDT EMISSIONS MODELS, WHILE ATAC SUPPORTED AEDT AIRCRAFT PERFORMANCE MODELING AND MOSAIC ATM HAVE EXTENSIVE EXPERIENCE WITH SMS. 5) INTEGRATION WITH SMS. AN INITIAL INTEGRATION OF THE DEVELOPED MODELS WITH SMS WILL BE CONDUCTED IN COLLABORATION WITH NASA, TO DEMONSTRATE THE ABILITY TO EVALUATE AND VISUALIZE THE O3 AND PM IMPACTS OF SURFACE OPERATIONS. LESSONS FROM THE INITIAL INTEGRATION WILL BE USED TO REFINE THE MODELS AS NEEDED. IN SUMMARY, THE RESEARCH TEAM WILL BRING TOGETHER EXTENSIVE EXPERTISE IN ASSESSING THE ENVIRONMENTAL IMPACTS OF AVIATION, AIRCRAFT AND ENGINE TECHNOLOGIES, OPERATIONAL PROCEDURES AND AIRPORT SURFACE MANAGEMENT APPROACHES, AND EXPERIENCE WITH BOTH SMS AND AEDT, TO DEVELOP, VALIDATE AND DEMONSTRATE MODELS FOR ASSESSING THE EMISSIONS IMPACTS OF AIRCRAFT OPERATIONS AT AIRPORTS.
